- [F-004-01] ADAPT the layer labels as a human-facing glossary only: Gem’s five layers are clear [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/README.md:117], but spec-kit already has spec levels, skills, and memory as distinct operational systems [SOURCE: CLAUDE.md:277] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/README.md:26] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/SKILL.md:409].
- [F-004-02] REJECT PRD-as-single-source-of-truth: Gem centralizes requirements in `docs/PRD.yaml` [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/README.md:121], while spec-kit’s equivalent is intentionally multi-document and level-based, including `decision-record.md` for architecture decisions [SOURCE: CLAUDE.md:281] [SOURCE: CLAUDE.md:283].
- [F-004-03] ADAPT the explicit priority order concept: Gem’s one-line order is valuable for ambiguity [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/AGENTS.md:60], while spec-kit currently has local precedence rules and a Logic-Sync halt rather than a global ordering [SOURCE: CLAUDE.md:116] [SOURCE: CLAUDE.md:310].
- [F-004-04] ADAPT memory ownership language: Gem’s orchestrator-only memory write/read path reduces drift [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/AGENTS.md:61], and spec-kit can express the same idea through existing `/memory:save`, canonical spec docs, and main-agent governance [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/SKILL.md:411] [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/orchestrate.md:376].
- [F-004-05] ADAPT Derived Docs as “external/reference evidence, lowest precedence”: Gem names `docs/knowledge/` and Context7 [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/README.md:125] [SOURCE: specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/gem-team-main/AGENTS.md:60], but spec-kit already routes knowledge through skill references and explicit search/retrieval tools [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/SKILL.md:84] [SOURCE: CLAUDE.md:100].

### NEGATIVE / RULED-OUT

- Do not adopt `docs/PRD.yaml` as a required artifact; spec-kit’s equivalent is `spec.md` plus plan/tasks/ADR/summary by level [SOURCE: CLAUDE.md:281] [SOURCE: CLAUDE.md:283].
- Do not adopt Gem’s exact priority order because “PRD before codebase” is too broad for spec-kit; implemented behavior and requirements can conflict, and spec-kit already requires Logic-Sync rather than silent precedence [SOURCE: CLAUDE.md:310].
- Do not add Context7 as a required named layer; spec-kit’s search routing and skill references already cover external/reference evidence [SOURCE: CLAUDE.md:100] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/SKILL.md:84].

### OPEN QUESTIONS

- Should spec-kit define separate priority orders by evidence type: requirements, implemented behavior, operational rules, and external docs?
- Should memory writes be explicitly main-agent/orchestrator-owned for all lanes, or only for canonical continuity saves?
- Should “external docs lowest unless cited/current” become a validation/checklist rule or just guidance?

